    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Office furniture that is a hybrid of cabinet and desk manufactured by Wooton and Company in Indianapolis in the latter part of the 19th century. These are characterized by two locking doors that themselves carry drawers and compartments for storage. When opened, a fall extends to create a writing surface facing an interior of ranged compartments and drawers.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051899/Wooton Patent Desks [exhibition catalog] (1983)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051904/Smithsonian Studies in History and Technology (2010-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>結合櫥櫃及寫字台的辦公室家具，十九世紀後半葉時，製於印第安納波里市的伍騰公司。在兩個可鎖住的門上裝有可儲物的抽屜及隔間。桌櫃打開後，會有寫字平台降下，與櫃門內成列的隔間和抽屜相對。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
